<section xml:id="sec-appG-numerical-differentiation-and-the-jacobian" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Numerical differentiation and the Jacobian</title>

  <subsection xml:id="appG-numdiff-forward-difference">
    <title>Forward difference</title>

    <p>
      For a one-variable function,
      <md>f'(a)\approx \frac{f(a+h)-f(a)}{h}.</md>
    </p>

    <p>This is simple but less accurate.</p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="appG-numdiff-central-difference">
    <title>Central difference</title>

    <p>
      <md>f'(a)\approx \frac{f(a+h)-f(a-h)}{2h}.</md>
    </p>

    <p>This is usually better.</p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="appG-numdiff-second-derivative">
    <title>Second derivative</title>

    <p>
      <md>f''(a)\approx \frac{f(a+h)-2f(a)+f(a-h)}{h^2}.</md>
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="appG-numdiff-partial-derivatives">
    <title>Partial derivatives</title>

    <p>
      For
      <md>f=f(x,y),</md>
      <md>f_x(a,b) \approx \frac{f(a+h,b)-f(a-h,b)}{2h}.</md>
      <md>f_y(a,b) \approx \frac{f(a,b+h)-f(a,b-h)}{2h}.</md>
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="appG-numdiff-gradient-by-central-differences">
    <title>Gradient by central differences</title>

    <program language="python">
      <input>
def grad2(f, x, y, h=1e-5):
    fx = (f(x+h, y) - f(x-h, y)) / (2*h)
    fy = (f(x, y+h) - f(x, y-h)) / (2*h)
    return np.array([fx, fy])
</input>
    </program>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="appG-numdiff-jacobian-matrix">
    <title>Jacobian matrix</title>

    <p>
      For
      <md>F:\mathbb R^n\to\mathbb R^m,</md>
      the Jacobian matrix is
      <md>
        J_F(\mathbf p)
        =
        \begin{pmatrix}
        \dfrac{\partial F_1}{\partial x_1} \amp \cdots \amp \dfrac{\partial F_1}{\partial x_n}\\[2mm]
        \vdots \amp \ddots \amp \vdots\\[2mm]
        \dfrac{\partial F_m}{\partial x_1} \amp \cdots \amp \dfrac{\partial F_m}{\partial x_n}
        \end{pmatrix}_{\mathbf p}.
      </md>
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="appG-numdiff-numerical-jacobian">
    <title>Numerical Jacobian</title>

    <program language="python">
      <input>
def jacobian(F, p, h=1e-5):
    p = np.array(p, dtype=float)
    m = len(F(p))
    n = len(p)
    J = np.zeros((m, n))

    for j in range(n):
        e = np.zeros(n)
        e[j] = 1.0
        J[:, j] = (F(p + h*e) - F(p - h*e)) / (2*h)

    return J
</input>
    </program>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="appG-numdiff-numerical-hessian">
    <title>Numerical Hessian</title>

    <p>
      For
      <md>f=f(x,y),</md>
      <md>f_{xx}\approx \frac{f(x+h,y)-2f(x,y)+f(x-h,y)}{h^2}.</md>
      <md>f_{yy}\approx \frac{f(x,y+h)-2f(x,y)+f(x,y-h)}{h^2}.</md>
      <md>f_{xy}\approx \frac{f(x+h,y+h)-f(x+h,y-h)-f(x-h,y+h)+f(x-h,y-h)}{4h^2}.</md>
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="appG-numdiff-symbolic-jacobian">
    <title>Symbolic Jacobian</title>

    <p>
      Using <c>SymPy</c>:
    </p>

    <program language="python">
      <input>
import sympy as sp

x, y = sp.symbols("x y")

F = sp.Matrix([
    x**2 + y,
    sp.sin(x*y)
])

J = F.jacobian([x, y])
</input>
    </program>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="appG-numdiff-symbolic-hessian">
    <title>Symbolic Hessian</title>

    <program language="python">
      <input>
f = x**3 + x*y + y**2
H = sp.hessian(f, (x, y))
</input>
    </program>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="appG-numdiff-step-size-warning">
    <title>Step-size warning</title>

    <warning>
      <p>
        If <m>h</m> is too large, the approximation error is large.
      </p>

      <p>
        If <m>h</m> is too small, roundoff error can dominate.
      </p>

      <p>
        A typical starting value is
        <md>h=10^{-5}</md>
        for central differences, but this is not universal.
      </p>
    </warning>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="appG-numdiff-differentiability-warning">
    <title>Differentiability warning</title>

    <warning>
      <p>
        Numerical derivatives can produce misleading numbers near:
      </p>

      <ol>
        <li>corners,</li>
        <li>cusps,</li>
        <li>jumps,</li>
        <li>singularities,</li>
        <li>rapid oscillations.</li>
      </ol>

      <p>
        A finite-difference approximation does not prove differentiability.
      </p>
    </warning>
  </subsection>
</section>
